com.habelitz.jsobjectizer.jsom.api.expression
Interface ClassConstructorCall

All Superinterfaces:
Expression, JSOM, PrimaryExpression
public interface ClassConstructorCall
extends PrimaryExpression

This PrimaryExpression type represents a new expression via a class constructor invocation, i.e. something like 'new AnyClassType(constructorArgs)'.

This class also supports inner new expressions for creating instances of an inner member class from outside the outer class. 

  OuterType outer = new OuterType();
  InnerType inner = outer.new InnerType(); // 'InnerType' is an inner member
                                           // class within 'OuterType'.
The difference between the two constructor invocation variants is that
  • inner new expressions are preceded by a primary expression (which is not a member of this class!) and ...
  • ... the constructor's name is never a qualified identifier, but always just a simple identifier for inner new expressions.

Author:
Dieter Habelitz
See Also:
for new expressions that instantiate static arrays.

getGenericTypeArguments

java.util.List<GenericTypeArgument> getGenericTypeArguments()
Returns a list of generic type arguments that may have been stated with the constructor invocation.

Example: new <T1> Foo<T2>(anyArgs)

For the example above this method would return list that contains just one generic type parameter that represents the type T1 stated by <T1>. The generic type argument <T2> would be part of the qualified identifier.

Calling this method equals an getGenericTypeArguments(null) call.

Returns:
A list of generic type arguments. If there are no generic type arguments null will be returned.
See Also:
getGenericTypeArguments(List)

getIdentifier

java.lang.String getIdentifier()
If this represents an inner new expression) this method returns the identifier of the constructor. Otherwise, i.e. for normal constructor calls, the last identifier from the qualified identifier will be returned.

Returns:
The identifier of the constructor, i.e. the type of the new instance.
See Also:
getGenericTypeArguments()

getQualifiedTypeIdentifier

java.util.List<ComplexTypeIdentifier> getQualifiedTypeIdentifier()
If this represents a standard constructor call (i.e. not the constructor call of an inner new expression) this method returns a list of identifiers representing a qualified identifier.

The first entry is the most left identifier and the last one is the type (i.e. the constructor) identifier. For the most trivial case only one identifier, the type identifier, will be added to the list.

Calling this method equals an getQualifiedTypeIdentifier(null) call.

Returns:
A list of identifiers representing a qualified identifier. If 'isInnerNewExpression() == true' null will be returned.
See Also:
getQualifiedTypeIdentifier(List), getIdentifier()
